    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "*This is a tracking issue, to provide an outline of what \"security\" means (or not) for Nvim.*\n\n### Problem\n\nvim/nvim have massive surface area, and almost any action can execute third-party plugin code, and shell commands. There is no meaningful way to make that \"secure\".\n\nHowever, there are some actions that should be safe by default. For example, we 100% want to avoid security risks from merely *reading* a file or directory.\n\nOutline of known attack vectors and mitigations:\n\n1. workspace-local auto-execution\n    1. ✅  'exrc'. Mitigation: hash the script contents, prompt if not in `:trust` db\n    2. ⚠️ (TODO) 'modeline', 'modelineexpr'. Mitigation: hash the filename+modeline, prompt if not in `:trust` db.\n        - https://github.com/neovim/neovim/issues/39044\n        - https://github.com/neovim/neovim/issues/25811\n    4. ⚠️ (TODO) `require('foo')` executes `foo.lua` from CWD (`package.path='./?.lua'`). https://github.com/neovim/neovim/issues/38966        - an exception can be made for `nvim -l`, but the default `package.path` needs to be modified for \"interactive\" use-case.\n    5. ❓ ftplugins (filetype plugins) can do arbitrary things, and they have a lot of surface area for mistakes, such as invoking `system()` on malicious filenames which may contain shell code.\n    6. `nvim://` URI [#38006](https://github.com/neovim/neovim/pull/38006)\n2. supply-chain attacks\n    1. Neovim CI. Mitigation: CI hardening, opsec\n    3. malicious treesitter parsers? Mitigation: WASM?\n3. Untrusted plugins.\n    - Mitigation: capabilities-based security model (leverage WASM interface). https://github.com/neovim/neovim/issues/23579\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nGather comments, then document the result.",
    "closed_at": null,
    "closed_by": null,
